05270nam a22006975i 9780226709406DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020003825  a97802267094067 a10.7208/97802267094062doi  a(DE-B1597)549527  a(OCoLC)1201195950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPR1261.C54bS47 2020 4aPR1261.C54bS47 2020 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a822/.0516089427142231 aSergi, Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPractical Cues and Social Spectacle in the Chester Plays /cMatthew Sergi. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote to the Reader -- tList of Tables -- tIntroduction: The Waterleaders’ Noah -- t1. Porousness and Diffusion in the Chester Goldsmiths’ Mise-en-Scène -- t2. Festive Piety: Food, Drink, and Recreation-as- Devotion in the Chester Plays -- t3. Cestrian Collaborations: Creating Texts, Casting, and Moving en Masse -- t4. In the Long Run: Practical Time in the Chester Plays -- t5. For the Lewd Standing Here: Chester’s Athletic Spectacles and Unruly Fans -- tConclusion: The Clothworkers’ Portents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Reading Alongside the EETS Edition -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmid the crowded streets of Chester, guild players portraying biblical characters performed on colorful mobile stages hoping to draw the attention of fellow townspeople. In the fifteenth and sixteenth centuries, these Chester plays employed flamboyant live performance to adapt biblical narratives. But the original format of these fascinating performances remains cloudy, as surviving records of these plays are sparse, and the manuscripts were only written down a generation after they stopped. Revealing a vibrant set of social practices encoded in the Chester plays, Matthew Sergi provides a new methodology for reading them and a transformative look at medieval English drama. Carefully combing through the plays, Sergi seeks out cues in the dialogues that reveal information about the original staging, design, and acting. These “practical cues,” as he calls them, have gone largely unnoticed by drama scholars, who have focused on the ideology and historical contexts of these plays, rather than the methods, mechanics, and structures of the actual performances. Drawing on his experience as an actor and director, he combines close readings of these texts with fragments of records, revealing a new way to understand how the Chester plays brought biblical narratives to spectators in the noisy streets. For Sergi, plays that once appeared only as dry religious dramas come to life as raucous participatory spectacles filled with humor, camp, and devotion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramazEnglandzChesteryTo 1500xHistory. 0aMysteries and miracle-plays, EnglishzEnglandzChesterxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aChester mystery cycle.  aChester plays.  aearly performance.  amedieval drama.  apractical cues.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyter